g.text: Update the diagram to update this service as a paid service where we charge $1 per month for the service.
We need to handle recurring payments and cancellations as well as handle sensitive customer data such as email addresses, phone numbers and credit card info.
1. AWS Lambda Function (Billing and Subscription Management):
A new Lambda function is added to handle billing and subscription management.
This function interacts with a payment gateway to handle recurring payments (e.g., Stripe, PayPal).
It manages customer subscriptions, including new subscriptions, cancellations, and billing updates.
The payment gateway integrates with the Lambda function to handle recurring payments.
It securely processes credit card information and manages subscription billing.
Payment details (such as credit card information) are securely stored and managed by the payment gateway, ensuring compliance with PCI DSS standards.
DynamoDB now stores additional sensitive customer data, including email addresses, phone numbers, and subscription status.
Customer data is securely encrypted at rest using AWS Key Management Service (KMS) to ensure data privacy and compliance.
Cognito is used for user authentication and identity management.
It securely manages user credentials and provides token-based authentication for accessing the system.
Cognito integrates with AWS Lambda for authorization checks and access control.
5. Amazon Simple Notification Service (SNS) and Amazon Simple Email Service (SES):
SNS and SES remain the same for sending SMS and email messages to subscribers.
They use subscriber information stored in DynamoDB to deliver messages securely.
CloudWatch Events are extended to trigger billing events, such as subscription renewals and payment failures.
The billing and subscription management Lambda function reacts to these events to ensure timely billing and subscription updates.
